"Please... side... please... give a little side..."

The voice wasn't loud.

Yet it somehow managed to cut through every other noise in the casualty corridor.

A man arguing at the billing counter stopped midway.

The ward boy pushing an oxygen cylinder looked back.

Even the tea seller outside the entrance lifted his head for a moment.

The stretcher wasn't moving.

A wheelchair had been left carelessly across the corridor.

The old ward boy pushing the stretcher shook his head.

"Every day..."

He pushed the wheelchair aside himself.

"...people think hospitals have roads wider than highways."

The girl walking beside the stretcher smiled faintly.

Not because she found it funny.

Because she had no energy left to react.

Her left elbow was bleeding.

The cotton sleeve had torn.

Dust still clung to her palms.

She had not even washed them.

The old man lying on the stretcher looked strangely peaceful.

His eyes remained closed.

A thin stream of dried blood had travelled from his forehead to his left ear.

His white cotton shirt had almost become brown near the shoulder.

One rubber slipper still remained on his right foot.

The other...

had probably remained somewhere on the road.

The girl suddenly stopped.

Bent down.

Removed the remaining slipper.

Placed both slippers carefully beneath the stretcher.

The ward boy looked at her.

"You know him?"

She shook her head.

"No."

"Then why..."

She simply smiled.

"It doesn't look nice..."

"...wearing only one slipper."

The old ward boy looked at her for two seconds.

Then quietly resumed pushing the stretcher.

Government hospitals teach people many things.

Kindness...

usually isn't one of them.

Yet sometimes...

someone unexpectedly remembers it.

"Casualty!"

the nurse shouted without looking up from her register.

"Case?"

"Road accident."

"Name?"

The ward boy looked at the girl.

The girl looked at the old man.

"...Budha Baba."

The nurse continued writing.

"Full name?"

"I don't know."

Now the nurse looked up.

"You don't know?"

"No."

"Father's name?"

"I don't know."

"Age?"

"Maybe..."

"...seventy."

"Address?"

"I don't know."

The nurse slowly closed the register.

"You brought an unknown old man to the hospital?"

The girl nodded.

"He was bleeding."

"So?"

"I brought him."

The nurse looked at her as though expecting another explanation.

None came.

The ward boy interrupted.

"Madam...

bike hit him near Saraswati Government School."

"Hit and run."

The nurse sighed.

"Every day..."

She reopened the register.

"Relationship?"

The pen remained waiting.

The girl didn't answer.

"Relative?"

"No."

"Daughter?"

"No."

"Neighbour?"

"No."

"Then?"

"I run an NGO nearby."

The nurse wrote.

NGO Volunteer.

"Sign here."

The girl signed without reading.

The stretcher disappeared inside the emergency room.

Only then did she realise...

she was still holding the old man's walking stick.

Nobody had noticed.

She looked at it carefully.

An ordinary bamboo stick.

Smooth near the handle.

Worn out near the bottom.

Someone had tied a tiny strip of red cloth at the top.

Perhaps to recognise it quickly.

She quietly kept it beside the ICU door.

As if the old man would immediately ask for it after waking up.

Inside...

the emergency room had already become another world.

"BP dropping."

"Pulse?"

"Seventy..."

"No... sixty-eight..."

"Suction."

"Gauze."

"Another IV line."

"Move."

One patient cried.

Another abused the hospital.

Somebody's child wouldn't stop coughing.

A woman fainted after seeing blood.

A ward boy searched for a missing oxygen mask.

Everything happened together.

Nobody had time to notice anyone else's problem.

Except...

the girl.

She stood outside the half-open door.

Every time someone crossed between her and the stretcher...

she instinctively shifted sideways to see whether the old man was still there.

As though he might quietly disappear if she lost sight of him.

"Madam."

She turned.

The receptionist stood holding a form.

"Admission."

She followed him.

Name.

Again she stopped.

Finally she wrote...

Budha Baba

Age.

Approximately 70.

Address.

Unknown.

Phone.

She wrote her own number.

The next column remained blank.

Relation with patient

The receptionist tapped the table.

"Madam..."

She held the pen.

Thought for a moment.

Then slowly wrote...

Human

The receptionist almost laughed.

"This is not an essay."

She looked at him.

"I know."

"Write proper relation."

She quietly struck it out.

Then wrote...

NGO Volunteer

At that exact moment...

the old Nokia phone inside her handbag started vibrating.

She looked at the screen.

School Office

She answered immediately.

"Hello."

"Didi...

children know."

"What?"

"They know Baba met with an accident."

"Who told them?"

"The auto uncle."

She closed her eyes.

"They're crying."

"I'll come later."

"No...

they're refusing lunch."

"I said I'll come."

She disconnected.

The phone vibrated again.

Milk Anna

Then...

Temple Pujari

Then...

Old Age Home

Then...

Vegetable Market

Every caller asked exactly one question.

"How is Baba?"

She answered every one of them exactly the same way.

"Doctor is treating him."

Within twenty minutes...

the corridor had started changing.

A flower seller arrived carrying two unsold garlands.

A school teacher came directly from class.

An old postman still wearing his faded khaki uniform.

A tailor.

A bus conductor.

A fruit vendor pushing his cart.

A college student carrying a backpack.

Nobody knew each other.

Yet every one of them walked to the same ICU door.

Nobody asked where to stand.

Nobody spoke loudly.

Nobody demanded updates.

They simply waited.

The receptionist slowly looked up from his computer.

Then towards the security guard.

"Who is this old man?"

The security guard shrugged.

"No idea."

"But..."

He looked outside.

"...the crowd keeps growing."